rijk"},"en":{"1460–1525":"1460–1525","1450–1501":"1450–1501","1457–1543":"1457–1543","1476–1560":"1476–1560","1478–1560":"1478–1560","1488–1521":"1488–1521","1434–Male":"1434–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1560":"1560","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","20 April 1501":"20 April 1501","1525":"1525","1457":"1457","1501":"1501","1478":"1478","1434":"1434","1488":"1488","1521":"1521","1543":"1543","1476":"1476","after 1521":"after 1521","Parish Church of Saint Mary and Saint Gabriel, South Harting, Chichester district, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"South Harting, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Harting, Sussex, England":"Harting, Sussex, England","Bratton Clovelly, Devon, England":"Bratton Clovelly, Devon, England","Harting, Chichester district, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Harting, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hussey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a nickname for someone who habitually wore a distinctive pair of boots or gaiters, from Old French <i>hosed</i>, <i>hoset</i>, <i>housé</i>, Middle English <i>hosey</i>, <i>hus(s)y</i>,‘booted, gaitered’ (from Latin <i>hosatus</i>).","English: status name or nickname from Middle English <i>hus(e)wyf</i> ‘mistress of a family; wife of a householder’ (a compound of Old English <i>hūs</i> ‘house’ + <i>wīf</i> ‘woman’). Though originally a woman's name, it is often found as a male surname, presumably in a derogatory sense. The vocabulary word became <i>hussie</i>, with the meaning ‘disreputable woman’, in the 16th century; the surname, however, is not associated with this meaning.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’. This was the name of a bardic family associated with the Maguires of Fermanagh, also Anglicized as   Oswell   or   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hosea","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  . Similarity with the Old Testament prophet's name Hosea (see 3 below) is accidental.","English: in Scotland, where the name is more common, it is sometimes a variant of   Hosie  , itself a form of   Hussey  , or else a variant of   Hossack  .","African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania): from the Biblical personal name <i>Hosea</i>. In the Old Testament, Hosea was a prophet who married a prostitute in order to illustrate Israel's unfaithfulness to God."]},{"name":"Hosie","meanings":["Scottish (northeast Scotland): variant of Irish   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Hassey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Oswell","meanings":["English: variant of   Oswald  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’ (see   Hussey  )."]},{"name":"Hosey","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  ."]}]},{"name":"Constance","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval form of the Late Latin name <i>Constantia</i>, which is either a feminine derivative of <i>Constans</i> (  see  Constant  ) or an abstract noun meaning ‘constancy’. This was a popular name among the Normans, and was borne by, amongst others, the formidable Constance of Sicily (  1158–98 ), wife of the Emperor  Henry VI ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Constance Hussey was born in 1460, in Harting, Sussex, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Nicholas Hussey and Barroness Alice Deincourt. She married Lord Henry Lovell of Harting, Sussex in 1476, in Harting, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. She died in 1525, in her hometown, at the age of 65, and was buried in South Harting, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1460–1525":"1460–1525","1450–1501":"1450–1501","1457–1543":"1457–1543","1476–1560":"1476–1560","1478–1560":"1478–1560","1488–1521":"1488–1521","1434–M